Simplify the code flow.

Loops only have thread-affinity while running. This means, we can
*run* a loop within any thread [in the Executor].

So: instead of creating loops per-thread, we create them
per-connection and allow that loop to run within any available thread.
Knowing that __init__() is a synchronous call, we can also move much
of the blocking connection-setup into the constructor.

With the above changes, we can also toss the per-thread initializer
and the mapping of thread/loop.

Allow for custom read buffer size and set a sane default

PyPubSub has a 256kb max payload size. The default read buffer for aiohttp is 64kb, which leads to many instances of "Chunk too big" exceptions. This bumps the default read buffer size to 300kb and allows it to be individually set.
